03789nam a22005175i 9780804777186DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202010cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047771867 a10.1515/97808047771862doi  a(DE-B1597)563642  a(OCoLC)1198929384  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aDS113.6b.D38 2011eb 7aHIS0190002bisacsh04a956.9400722221 aDavis, Rochelle, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPalestinian Village Histories :bGeographies of the Displaced /cRochelle Davis. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (360 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStanford Studies in Middle Eastern and Islamic Societies and Cultures00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of illustrations -- tNote on translations and transliterations -- tAcknowledgements -- tPreface -- t1. Geographies of dispossession -- t2. Village books: local histories, national struggles -- t3. Village history and village values -- t4. Writing a history, defining a past -- t5. The authority of memory -- t6. Mapping the past: the village landscape -- t7. Identities and history -- t8. Conclusion: connecting geographies of dispossession -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThroughout modern-day Israel, over four hundred Palestinian villages were depopulated in the 1947-1949 war. With houses mostly destroyed, mosques and churches put to other uses, and cemeteries plowed under, Palestinian communities were left geographically dispossessed. Palestinians have since carried their village names, memories, and possessions with them into the diaspora, transforming their lost past into local histories in the form of "village memorial books". Numbering more than 100 volumes in print, these books recount family histories, cultural traditions, and the details of village life, revealing Palestinian history through the eyes of Palestinians. Through a close examination of these books and other commemorative activities, Palestinian Village Histories reveals how history is written, recorded, and contested, as well as the roles that Palestinian conceptions of their past play in contemporary life. Moving beyond the grand narratives of 20th century political struggles, this book analyzes individual and collective historical accounts of everyday life in pre-1948 Palestinian villages as composed today from the perspectives of these long-term refugees.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aPalestinian ArabsxHistoriography. 0aVillageszPalestinexHistoriography. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Israel & Palestine.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080477718640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804777186423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804777186.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles